Find the greatest common divisor of $10293$ and $29384$.
inference:
$\newline$
**Step 1. Find the prime factorizations of $10293$ and $29384$**
$\newline$
$$10293=3\times3\times3\times3\times3\times3=3^6$$

$$29384=2\times2\times2\times2\times2\times2\times2\times2\times7=2^8\times7$$

**Step 2. Find the common factors of $10293$ and $29384$**
$\newline$
The common factors are $3^3=27$ and $2^2=4$.
$\newline$
**Step 3. Multiply the common factors to find the greatest common divisor**
$\newline$
$$\text{GCD}(10293,29384)=27\times4=\boxed{108}.$$
$\newline$
Final Answer: \boxed{$108$}. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
We use the Euclidean algorithm to find the greatest common divisor. \begin{align*}
\text{gcd}\,(10293,29384) &=\text{gcd}\,(29384-2 \cdot 10293,10293)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(8798,10293)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(8798,10293-8798)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(8798,1495)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(8798-1495 \cdot 5 ,1495)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(1323,1495)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(1323,1495-1323)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(1323,172)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(1323-172 \cdot 7 ,172)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(119,172)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(119,172-119)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(119,53)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(119-53 \cdot 2,53)\\
&=\text{gcd}\,(13,53).\\
\end{align*}At this point we can see that since $53$ is not divisible by the prime number $13$, the greatest common divisor is just $\boxed{1}$.
